# Public Prosecutor _v_ Yeduvaka Mali Naidu  

### \[2022\] SGDC 173

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Sentencing

Criminal Law – Statutory offences – Workplace Safety and Health Act - Doing a reckless act without reasonable cause

\[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9140/2022/01.\]

5 August 2022

### District Judge Lorraine Ho:

## Introduction

1       The accused, a 37-year-old male Indian national, was employed as a supervisor cum forklift operator in Singapore by Chye Joo Marine Pte Ltd (“Chye Joo”).

2       On 2 June 2022, the accused pleaded guilty to a singular charge for recklessly doing an act on 26 May 2019 which endangered the safety of himself or others at a workplace located at 1 Benoi Road Singapore 629875 (“Worksite”) without reasonable cause. He did so by allowing one Shanmugam Sivarasu (“Shanmugam”) to operate a Komatsu forklift (“K-Forklift”) without attaining the relevant training to do so and with the knowledge that the K-Forklift brakes were faulty. This resulted in the death of his co-worker, Rahman Zillur (“the Deceased”).

3       At the same time, Shanmugam, who was also a co-worker of the accused, pleaded guilty to a charge for recklessly doing an act which endangered the safety of others at the Worksite without reasonable cause by operating the K-Forklift without attaining the relevant training to do so and with the knowledge that the K-Forklift’s brakes were faulty. This resulted in the death of the Deceased.

4       At the hearing, both the accused and Shanmugam were represented by Defence Counsel assigned under the Enhanced Guidance for Plea Scheme (“EGPS”) administered by the State Courts’ Community Justice Centre.

5       I imposed a sentence of seven months’ imprisonment on the accused with the sentence backdated to the date of his remand on 22 March 2022.

6       I imposed a sentence of 11 months’ imprisonment on Shanmugam with the sentence backdated to the date of his remand on 22 March 2022.

7       On 25 July 2022, being dissatisfied with the sentence imposed on the accused, the Prosecution filed a Notice of Appeal.

## Background facts

### The Charge

8       The proceeded charge against the accused reads as follows:

<table align="left" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="Judg-2-tblr" frame="all" pgwide="1"><colgroup><col width="29.72%"><col width="70.28%"></colgroup><tbody><tr><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Charge No.</b></p></td><td align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Description of the Charge</b></p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="r" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">DSC-900090-2022</p></td><td align="left" class="" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">You, are charged that you, on or before 26 May 2019, being a person at work at a worksite located at 1 Benoi Road Singapore 629875, which was a workplace within the meaning of the Workplace Safety and Health Act (Chapter 354A, Rev Ed 2009) (“the Act”), did without reasonable cause, recklessly do any act which endangers the safety or health of himself or others; to wit, you allowed an untrained forklift operator, Shanmugam Sivarasu (“Shanmugam”) (FIN: GXXXX077N), to operate one Komatsu forklift which had faulty brakes, which endangered the safety of persons working at the worksite and resulted in the death of Rahman Zillur (FIN: GXXXX776P) and you have thereby committed an offence under section 15(3) of the Act, punishable under the section 50(a) of the Act.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>

  
  

### Statement of facts

9       The accused admitted to the Statement of Facts (“SOF”) dated 12 May 2022 without qualification.

#### The Parties

10     East Marine Pte. Ltd. (“EMPL”) owed a fleet of vessels. Asia Pacific-Shipyard Pte. Ltd. (“APS”) operated a shipyard (“the shipyard”) located at the Worksite, which was a workplace within the meaning of the Workplace Safety and Health Act (Cap 354A, 2009 Rev Ed) (“WHSA”).

11     EMPL and APS shared common directors. EMPL and APS signed a long-term agreement where EMPL would pay a monthly sum to APS for the maintenance and repair of their vessels. As part of this long-term agreement, APS was required to service and repair one of its vessels, Tolak Tiga (“the vessel”). This included grit blasting and painting of the vessel’s external hull. EMPL contracted Chye Joo Services to carry out the grit-blasting and painting works. The works were to be managed by APS as the occupier. Chye Joo Services sub-contracted the works to Chye Joo. The Deceased was employed by Chye Joo as a painter and blaster since 6 May 2013. He was further deployed on numerous occasions to work at the shipyard.

#### The Accident

12     In essence, the fatal accident occurred on 26 May 2019. Six employees from Chye Joo were assigned to work at the Worksite that day. They included the Deceased, the accused, Shanmugam and one Dinesh Subramaniam (“Subramaniam”). The working team was performing spray-painting works of the vessel. The team did so between 9am to 1pm and continued with the works at 2.30pm.

13     At about 3pm, a forklift operator from APS, Velu Prakashraj (“**Velu**”), parked a Mitsubishi forklift (“M-Forklift”) in front of the Lifting Store & Container (“the Container”). Shortly after, the accused went to the Container and sought permission from Velu to use the M-Forklift.

14     Investigations revealed that it was the practice of APS’ forklift operators to allow Chye Joo’s certified forklift operator to use their forklifts within the shipyard when they no longer needed to use them. As Velu knew that the accused was a certified forklift operator, he allowed the accused to use the M-Forklift. Velu informed the accused that the brakes of the M-Forklift were not effective (i.e. when the brake pedal was depressed, there was no pressure felt until the pedal was almost touching the floor). However, the accused had insisted on using the M-Forklift as he explained that it was only for a short duration.

15     At 5pm, the Deceased was roller-painting the waterline markings on the body of the ship. At about the same time, the accused went to seek permission to use the K-Forklift, which was a powered counterbalanced Komatsu forklift, but none of APS’s employees were around. Whereas functional forklifts require an ignition key to start, the K-Forklift was faulty and could be started without any key. The accused knew this and used his locker key to operate the K-Forklift.

16     Between 5.02pm to 5.40pm, the K-Forklift was used by the accused and Shanmugam to transfer spray-painting equipment.

17     At about 5.40pm, accused proceeded to lift a blasting pot using the M-Forklift. Subramaniam assisted to raise the chain of the blasting pot to allow the accused to insert one of the forks under the chain to lift the blasting pot. After lifting the blasting pot, the accused reversed the M-Forklift. The accused then drove the M-Forklift towards the storage area and another worker hopped in to assist him at the storage area.

![](data:image;base64,)

18     At the same time, Shanmugam returned from the storage area and proceeded to position the K-Forklift in front of the M-Forklift. Shanmugam was driving the K-Forklift towards another blasting pot placed on the driveway and along the guardrail to transport it. He realised that the position of the forks was too low as the blasting pot was half a metre away from the tip of the K-Forklift. He had to raise the forks of the K-Forklift in order to reach and lift the blasting pot.

19     Shanmugam forgot that the K-Forklift was placed in forward gear instead of neutral gear. He pressed on the acceleration pedal when he wanted to raise the forks quickly. Instead, the entire K-Forklift accelerated forward. Shanmugam failed to press on the brake pedal as the K-Forklift surged forward. Shanmugam had knowledge that the brakes of the K-Forklift were faulty.

20     Subramaniam, who was assisting Shanmugam by holding onto the chain of the blasting pot, shouted ‘stop’ loudly. He dropped the chain as the K-Forklift started approaching rapidly and he feared that it might hit him. Subramaniam managed to move away from the path of the K-Forklift before the K-Forklift could strike him directly. As a result, Subramaniam sustained minor injuries.

21     The K-Forklift crashed through the guardrail along the edge of a slipway, fell onto the slipway together with the blasting pot. The blasting pot and the K-Forklift struck the Deceased who was walking on the slipway at the material time.

![](data:image;base64,)

22     SCDF arrived shortly and the Deceased was pronounced dead at the scene. The cause of death was certified as “multiple injuries” Subramaniam sustained a minor scratch on his right shin and swelling on his left foot whilst Shanmugam sustained abrasions on both shins. Subramaniam and Shanmugam were brought to the hospital for treatment and were each given three days of medical leave.

#### The Accused’s Reckless Act

23     Investigations revealed that the accused, as a supervisor at work, had a duty not to do any reckless act which endangers the safety or health of himself or others.

24     This was because the accused, being Shanmugam’s supervisor, had allowed Shanmugam to operate forklifts on multiple occasions despite knowing that Shanmugam was not certified, trained and competent to operate a forklift. The accused was aware of the risks that an accident could happen because Shanmugam was not licensed to operate the K-Forklift. Shanmugam did not attend any forklift training and only knew how to operate forklifts by observing others.

25     The accused was also involved in the development of Chye Joo’s risk assessment (“RA”) for work activities such as “Grit Blasting” and “Spray Painting”. The hazards of forklift crashing into other vehicles or objects and workers being hit by forklifts were identified in Chye Joo’s RA. The RA also noted the hazard of a forklift toppling over due to unauthorised operating of forklifts. One of the control measures identified by Chye Joo was to ensure that the operator must be trained and competent to operate a forklift.

26     Despite this, the accused had allowed Shanmugam, an untrained person, to operate the K-Forklift. The accused also failed to inform his employer that he had allowed Shanmugan to operate the K-Forklift.

27     The accused was also aware that the brakes of the forklifts being used at the Worksite were faulty. Nonetheless, the accused allowed Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift. The accused had also operated the M-Forklifts himself.

## Antecedents

28     The accused was untraced.

## Prosecution’s submissions on sentence

29     The Prosecution tendered written submissions. The Prosecution submitted a sentence of 12 months’ imprisonment to be imposed on the accused.

30     For the record, the Prosecution similarly submitted a sentence of 12 months’ imprisonment to be imposed on Shanmugam.

31     As there is currently no decision from the High Court on the applicable sentencing framework for offences under s 15(3) of WHSA, the Prosecution submitted a proposed two-step sentencing framework for s 15(3) of WHSA offence. This was primarily based on the High Court decision of _Mao Xuezhong_ <span class="citation">\[2020\] 5 SLR 580</span> (_“Mao”_), which dealt with an offence of doing a negligent act under s 15(3A) (now s 15(4)) of the WHSA. Following from _Mao_, harm would include both actual and potential harm.

32     However, the range of sentences under each of the harm-culpability category has been modified from _Mao_ and calibrated upwards accordingly to utilise the entire sentencing range of the punishment prescribed by law for performing a more serious reckless or wilful act under s 15(3) and punishable under s 50(a) of WHSA. The upward adjustment reflects a higher mental culpability. The proposed sentencing framework for an offender who claims trial is as follows:

![](data:image;base64,)

33     Following from _Mao_, the Prosecution elaborated that, in its assessment, low/medium rashness is broadly comparable to medium /high negligence respectively and the sentencing bands reflect this. The rationale is to not only reflect the relative severity of the offences under s 15(3) of WHSA as compared to s 15(4), but also allow for short custodial terms to be imposed if the offenders are unable to afford the high fines of $100,000 to $200,000.

34     In the two-step approach, Prosecution submitted that the factors which are relevant in the determination of the levels of culpability and harm to derive the indicative starting point according to the sentencing framework for the first step are as set out at \[64(a)\] of _Mao_. They are as follows:

> (a)     Factors relevant to culpability:

>> (i)       nature of the unsafe act;

>> (ii)       number of unsafe acts committed by the offender;

>> (iii)       level of deviation from established procedure;

>> (iv)       whether the breaches were systemic or whether they were part of an isolated incident; and

>> (v)       whether the breaches were intentional, rash or negligent.

> (b)     Factors relevant to harm:

>> (i)       whether any death was caused;

>> (ii)       extent of injury caused;

>> (iii)       seriousness of harm risked;

>> (iv)       likelihood of harm arising;

>> (v)       number of people likely to be exposed to the risk of harm.

35     As for the second step to consider any adjustment of the starting point sentence according to offender-specific aggravating and mitigating factors that have yet to be factored into the analysis, they included the following as set out at \[107\] and \[108\] in the High Court decision of _Nurun Novi v PP_ <span class="citation">\[2019\] 3 SLR 413</span> (_“Nurun Novi”_):

> (a)     Aggravating factors:

>> (i)       whether the offender obtained financial gain from the breaches or had cut cost at the expense of safety of the workers;

>> (ii)       the existence of relevant antecedents;

>> (iii)       deliberate concealment of the illegal nature of the activity; and

>> (iv)       obstruction of justice.

> (b)     Mitigating factors:

>> (i)       a high level of cooperation with the authorities, beyond that which is normally expected; and

>> (ii)       a timely plea of guilt; and the voluntary taking of steps to remedy the breach or prevent future occurrences of similar breaches.

36     Applying the proposed sentencing framework, the Prosecution was of the view that the level of harm, both actual and potential harm, was high for both the accused and Shanmugam.

37     For actual harm, this was high as death was caused because of the accident. Subramaniam also sustained minor injuries when he was trying to avoid being hit by the K-Forklift.

38     The Prosecution explained that in respect of the accused, he knew that Shanmugam was not a certified or trained forklift operator. Despite this, the accused continued allowing Shanmugam to operate forklifts, including the K-Forklift on the day of the accident.

39     Although the accused’s act of allowing Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift might have been slightly more remote as compared to Shanmugam’s direct act of operating the K-Forklift, Prosecution was of the view that this could be considered an enabling factor which ultimately led to the Deceased’s death. Therefore, if the accused, as a supervisor, had stopped or forbidden Shanmugam from operating the K-Forklift in the first place, this might have prevented the accident altogether.

40     Apart from actual harm, the Prosecution submitted that potential harm was also high. Not only did the accused allowed Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift, he himself had also operated the M-Forklift. Further, despite being told by Velu that the brakes of the M-Forklift were faulty, he made a conscious decision to operate the M-Forklift since there were no other forklifts to complete the work.

41     The Prosecution added that the likelihood of harm being caused to others is high when a person operates a forklift without training. Such a risk increases tremendously when the untrained person operates it in an inherently unsafe manner, i.e. raising the forks of a forklift when travelling and operating forklifts with faulty brakes. It was highly likely that accidents could happen and worse, unpreventable due to faulty brakes like in the present case.

42     As for the seriousness of the harm risked, the Prosecution elaborated that this was also high since both the brakes of the K-Forklift and the M-Forklift were faulty. This was exacerbated when the K-Forklift accelerated and its brakes were not functional. On top of that, the K-Forklift pushed the blasting pot into the slipway and this increased the gravity of the harm. Not only were the workers working below the slipway to paint the vessel exposed to the risk, the workers on the ground, such as Subramaniam who was assisting with the lifting of the chain of the blasting pot, were similarly exposed to the risk of being hit by the K-Forklift as the brakes could not be applied effectively.

43     As for culpability, the Prosecution was of the view that this should also be the same at high for both the accused and Shanmugam.

44     Generally, the operation of a forklift poses serious safety concerns to persons. Prosecution was therefore of the view that it is vital for an operator to exercise great caution when using a forklift.

45     Specifically in respect of the accused, the Prosecution submitted that the accused had authorised an untrained forklift operator to operate the K-Forklift. Moreover, the accused knew that the brakes of the forklifts at the Worksite were faulty. Nonetheless, he not only allowed Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift, but he similarly operated the M-Forklift with faulty brakes. This demonstrated that the accused had little regard for his own safety as well as the safety of others at the Worksite.

46     Further, even though the accused was not the operator of the K-Forklift at the material time, Prosecution emphasised that as Shanmugam’s supervisor, he had greater responsibilities. The accused had the authority to disallow Shanmugam from operating forklifts as he was untrained, uncertified and unqualified. It was convenient for the accused to assume that it was safe for Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift as the latter had operated them on many occasions without any incident. Here, the breaches committed were therefore systemic.

47     Yet, the accused was involved in the review of the risk assessment (“RA”) relating to the use of forklifts for work activities such as “Grit Blasting” and “Spray Painting”. Hence, he knew that an untrained operator should not be operating forklifts at all times. To compound matters, the Prosecution added that the accused had also failed to inform his employer when he allowed Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift.

48     In the circumstances, Prosecution submitted that the accused could be said to be reckless and his culpability for this reckless act was high.

49     When asked who was in charge of maintaining the forklifts at the Worksite, the Prosecution informed that the forklifts belonged to the occupier, APS. APS had a team of mechanics who were supposed to maintain the forklifts. There was evidence that the forklifts were not maintained properly at the Worksite. For example, the M-Forklift had several technical issues besides having faulty brakes. There was also evidence that the workers of Chye Joo had informed the maintenance team that the forklifts were not in a good operating condition. Nonetheless the workers at the Worksite were allowed to continue using these forklifts to perform the works.

50     As for work procedures for the transportation of the blasting pot at the Worksite, the Prosecution informed the court that the only method to do so was by using the forklifts given the weight of the blasting pot. Even though there were no other forklifts which were properly maintained, as a supervisor and forklift operator, the Prosecution was of the view that the accused retained the authority to decline performing the works until safe equipment was provided to him and his workers in the interest of safety. At the same time, the Prosecution informed the court that action will be taken against the occupier for its failure to maintain the forklifts.

51     Coming back to the proposed sentencing framework, in view of the high harm and the accused’s high culpability in the present case, the sentencing range is a term of imprisonment of more than 15 months and up to 24 months. The Prosecution submitted that an indicative starting sentence of 15 months’ imprisonment was appropriate.

52     The Prosecution referred the court to two unreported cases for the offence under s 15(3) of WSHA. The first was the connected cases of _PP v Wong Kiew Hai_ (SC-903990- 2018) (“_Wong_”) and _PP v Yee Chee Keong_ (SC-904891-2018) (“_Yee_”). Due to the collapse of a section of the viaduct, one worker was killed and ten others seriously injured. _Yee_ was sentenced to ten months’ imprisonment for failing to do anything to call for stoppage of works prior to the collapse when he had prior knowledge about cracks that had appeared on multiple corbels of the viaduct and he was informed about fresh cracks which appeared moments before its collapse. _Wong_ was sentenced to eight months’ imprisonment for failing to call for a stoppage of works despite appreciating the seriousness of the situation when he knew about the cracks on the corbels of the viaduct and had ample opportunity to do so.

53     The second was the case of _PP v Mamun AL_ (DSC-900046-2020) (“_Mamun_”), where the accused was sentenced to 42 weeks’ imprisonment for operating a forklift without being certified to do so and in a dangerous matter. This resulted in the victim sustaining serious injuries. The Prosecution was of the view that a higher sentence is warranted for the accused in the present case as the accused was a supervisor and a key member of the RA team to ensure the compliance of safety protocols. Yet, he deliberately allowed Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift. Furthermore, besides greater actual harm caused in the present case, there were more workers being exposed to the risk as compared to _Mamun_.

54     Finally, as the accused had pleaded guilty at the earliest opportunity, was untraced and remorseful for his acts, the Prosecution suggested a downward calibration of the starting sentence to take into account the mitigating factors. Thus, the Prosecution was of the view that a sentence of at least 12 months’ imprisonment was appropriate in the circumstances.

## Mitigation

55     Besides submitting a handwritten mitigation, Defence Counsel assigned under the EGPS Scheme made oral submissions on his behalf.

56     In his handwritten mitigation, the accused pleaded for leniency and requested for a lower sentence. The accused stated that he was working for Chye Joo in Singapore for 14 years and he had been a safety supervisor for almost nine years. Over the years, he had a good safety record until the accident. After the accident, he continued to work for his company for almost three years without any incident.

57     The accused was married in 2018 and was a sole breadwinner supporting his wife, his three-year-old daughter and elderly parents in India. The accused was extremely sorry to the Deceased and his family and accepted responsibility for his actions. He had co-operated fully with the Ministry of Manpower during investigations and pleaded guilty at the first available opportunity.

58     Defence Counsel was agreeable to the Prosecution’s proposed sentencing framework.

59     The Defence submitted for a sentence of seven months’ imprisonment to be imposed on the accused.

60     The Defence submitted for a sentence of nine to ten months’ imprisonment to be imposed on Shanmugam.

61     As regards harm, the Defence was of the view that this should be at the higher end of moderate vis-à-vis the accused. This was to take into account the fact that the actual harm from the accident was not caused by the accused but by Shanmugam. The recklessness in the accused’s offence was to allow Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift even though he was untrained. The reckless act did not include the operation of the K-Forklift itself by Shanmugam resulting in the accident and the Deceased’s death.

62     The Defence hence submitted that when assessing actual harm cause, it would be too remote to attribute this to the accused.

63     As for potential harm, the Defence submitted that this would still be at the higher end of moderate for two reasons. First, the accused himself had operated the M-Forklift which was not effective. He also allowed Shanmugam to operate a faulty K-Forklift. Second, at the Worksite, there were a few workers working in the vicinity when Shanmugam was operating the K-Forklift.

64     For culpability, the Defence said that should be in the middle of moderate because even though the accused was Shanmugam’s supervisor and he should not have allowed Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift without certification, the issue of the faulty brakes was not attributable to him as he was not responsible for the maintenance of the forklifts. In fact, there was evidence from investigations that the workers did raise this issue to the maintenance team about the condition of the forklifts at the Worksite which were owned by the occupier.

65     Therefore, based on the Prosecution’s proposed sentencing framework, the indicative sentencing range would be between more than three months and up to nine months’ imprisonment. The Defence cautioned that the entire sentencing framework was intended for both reckless and wilful acts, the latter being more serious in terms of mental culpability. The accused’s act in this case was a reckless act and hence should not fall under the higher end of the sentencing matrix.

66     Defence counsel submitted that the indicative starting sentence ought to be nine months’ imprisonment. Reference can be made using the case of _Mamun_ as tendered by the Prosecution. The culpability of the offender in _Mamun_ was higher than Shanmugam in the present case as in _Mamun_, the offender, who similarly operated a forklift without being certified, had operated it dangerously by driving at high speed and with the mast of the forklift raised when the forklift was in motion.

67     In the accused’s case, given that he did not cause the accident, his reckless act was confined to allowing Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift without being trained to do so. Added to that, having taken into account the mitigating factors of the accused, including the fact that he has pleaded guilty, is remorseful and untraced, a downward adjustment of the sentence to seven months’ imprisonment would be fair in the circumstances.

## Reply

68     The Prosecution submitted that even though the accused did not directly cause the accident, there was a contributory link to the actual harm caused from his reckless act. The Prosecution referred to _Mao_ at \[64(a)(i)\] where it was held by the High Court that actual harm caused could be a causal or contributory link to the risk created by an accused person’s negligent act.

69     The Prosecution elaborated that in _Mao_, the accused did not give his workers instructions to carry out the unsafe acts. However, when he instructed his workers to go onto the protruding table platform, the accused failed to ensure that the deceased had secured his safety harness to an anchorage point before descending. Similarly, in the present case, while the Prosecution accepted that the faulty brakes of the K-Forklift did not directly result in the accident, when the accused instructed Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift with faulty brakes, he did this knowing that Shanmugam was untrained to do so. Thus, at the very least, there was a contributory link to the actual harm caused.

## Decision on sentence

70     The issue before me was the appropriate sentence to impose on the accused and whether, on the facts and the proceeded charge, the accused ought to be imposed the same sentence as Shanmugam.

71     Sections 15(3) and 50(a) of the WHSA state:

> **Duties of persons at work**

> 15 - (3) – Any person at work who, without reasonable cause, wilfully or recklessly does any act which endangers the safety or health of himself or others shall be guilty of an offence.

> **General penalties**

> Section 50(a) – Any person guilty of an offence under this Act (but not including the regulations) for which no penalty is expressly provided by this Act shall be liable on conviction, in the case of a natural person, to a fine not exceeding $200,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 2 years or to both.

72     Under No. 2 of the Factories (Safety Training Courses) Order (S 207/2001, Rev Ed 2002), it is stated as follows:

> The occupier of a factory shall ensure that the classes or description of persons employed in the factory set out in the first column of the Schedule attend the safety training courses conducted by the Occupational Safety and Health Training and Promotion Centre or other training institutions approved by the Chief Inspector set out opposite thereto in the second column thereof.

In the Schedule, a forklift operator, who is defined as any person who drives or operates a forklift truck in a factory, shall attend the Forklift Driver’s Training Course.

73     The legislative intent of the WHSA was essentially to improve workplace safety by ensuring that employers and other stakeholders take proactive steps to avert poor safety management and prevent workplace accidents through the imposition of higher penalties where appropriate as a matter of deterrence. The applicable penalty in any given case can even occur in situations where no accidents happened and will take into consideration the culpability of the offender, the potential harm that could have been caused and the harm actually done. This has been highlighted in several High Court decisions including _Mao_ at \[47\] and \[67\] and most recently in _PP v Manta Equipment (S) Pte Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGHC 157</span> at \[23\] and \[24\] (_“Manta”_):

> \[23\]…\[I\]t is therefore useful to set out below the relevant portions of the speech by Dr Ng Eng Hen, the then-Minister for Manpower(_Singapore Parliamentary Debates, Official Report_ (17 January 2006), vol 80 at cols 2206 and 2215):

>> Third, this Bill will better define persons who are accountable, their responsibilities and institute penalties which reflect the true economic and social cost of risks and accidents. Penalties should be sufficient to deter risk-taking behaviour and ensure that companies are proactive in preventing incidents. Appropriately, companies and persons that show poor safety management should be penalised even if no accident has occurred.

>> …

>> The Factories Act contains a stepped penalty regime based on the harm done. The inadequacy of this regime is that it does not allow for meaningful penalties in cases where there are severe lapses, but fortuitously no accidents have occurred. Under the Bill, a single maximum penalty is prescribed. However, _the penalty, in any given case, will be applied taking into account all the relevant circumstances, including the culpability of the offender, the potential harm that could have been caused, and the harm actually done._

>> \[emphasis original\]

> \[24\]  As noted by Dr Ng, the Act was intended to address the “inadequacy of the penalty regime of its predecessor, which was concerned solely with actual harm. To that end, the Act sought to deter poor safety management and effect a cultural change for employers and other stakeholders to take proactive measures to prevent accidents at the workplace, as was rightly pointed out in _GS Engineering_ at \[51\]. However, the fact that Parliament consciously sought to expand the recognition of harm in the Act to include potential harm does not necessarily mean that potential harm was thereafter to be accorded precedence over other factors. We note that Dr Ng’s explanation of “all the relevant circumstances” listed culpability, potential harm and actual harm without giving primacy to any of them. _The better understanding of the Act, in our opinion, is that it was not meant to displace the significance of actual harm, but was instead meant to give effect to a more nuanced notion of “harm”: not just “risks and accidents”, but the underlying “economic and social cost” as well_. \[emphasis added\]

74     As the interplay between culpability and harm are to be given equally important considerations for an offence under s 15(4) of WHSA arising from a negligent act, a two-stage sentencing framework was set out by the High Court in _Mao_ at \[64(a)(iii)\] to provide guidance to the court when determining the appropriate sentences of such offenders.

75     In _Manta_, the High Court, in _obiter dicta_, was of the provisional view that the two-stage sentencing approach as set out in _Mao_ should remain applicable to offenders punishable under s 50(a) of WHSA with the distinction that the mental culpability of an offender who is reckless or wilful will be considered higher than one who is negligent. At \[37\], Steven Chong JCA said:

> Nonetheless, we are of the view that the overall two-stage sentencing approach we have outlined above should remain applicable to natural persons punishable under s 50(_a_). Where the same duty to take reasonably practicable measures to ensure safety and health applies, the same considerations surrounding harm, culpability and the relevant aggravating and mitigating factors prevail, notwithstanding that the offender is a natural person. This should extend to s 13(1) as well, which is also framed with reference to reasonably practicable measures necessary to ensure safety and health. Similarly, while the mental element encapsulated in s 15(3) – wilfulness or recklessness – is different from the negligence that characterises the other offences punishable under s 50(_a_), we are of the provisional view that the two-stage sentencing approach should remain applicable. Preliminarily, we observe that an offender who is reckless or wilful will be considered to be of higher culpability, subject to other factors relevant to the assessment of culpability.

76     Therefore, I agreed with both the Prosecution and Defence that the two-stage sentencing framework in _Mao_ could be modified and calibrated accordingly to deal with the more serious reckless or wilful act under s 15(3) of WHSA. I further agreed that the factors as set out in \[64(a)\] of _Mao_ are relevant when determining the degree of harm caused as well as an accused’s level of culpability based on the facts of each case.

77     Under s 15(4) of WHSA, the maximum punishment prescribed by law is a fine not exceeding $30,000 or an imprisonment term not exceeding two years or both. Under s 15(3) which is an offence punishable under s 50(a) of WHSA, the maximum fine amount prescribed by law is higher at $200,000 but the maximum imprisonment term prescribed by law remains at two years. In order to utilise the entire sentencing range of the punishment prescribed by law for an offence under s 15(3) of WHSA, I accepted the Prosecution’s proposed sentencing framework as set out earlier in the Prosecution’s submissions on sentence.

78     I only wish to add that the Prosecution’s proposed sentencing framework for s 15(3) of WHSA deals with situations of both reckless and wilful acts, with an act of wilfulness being of greater culpability than that of recklessness. A wilful act is an intentional, premeditated or deliberate act. On the other hand, a reckless act is one which is rash, thoughtless, hasty and perhaps even foolhardy. As such, unlike the sentencing framework for s 15(4) of WHSA which only deals with negligent acts, in my view, the sentence ranges for high level of culpability should generally be reserved for wilful acts.

79     Additionally, sentences at or close to the prescribed maximum imprisonment term should generally be reserved for the types of disasters that involve significant loss of life or great loss to the economy and severe inconveniences to the public as stated at \[68\] in _Mao_. This, for example, would be something close to the scale of the Nicoll Highway collapse.

### Application of the proposed sentencing framework to the present case

#### Harm

80     On the issue of harm vis-à-vis the accused, I agreed with the Prosecution that this should be the same as Shanmugam at high. I now give my reasons.

81     As a result of the accident, death of a worker occurred. Although this was not stated in the charge but the SOF, another co-worker, Subramaniam sustained minor injuries when he moved away to avoid the moving K-Forklift.

82     As death did occur, as mentioned in both _Mao_ at \[64(a)\] and _Manta_ at \[45\], harm should be positioned near the top end of the high range.

83     In respect of the causation of the actual harm, Prosecution agreed with the Defence that it would be too remote to attribute the death of the Deceased to the accused. This was because the actual harm caused to both the Deceased and Subramaniam was directly caused by Shanmugam’s reckless act of operating the K-Forklift.

84     At the same time, I agreed with the Prosecution that the accused had played a contributory and indirect role by permitting or authorising Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift that day when he was not certified or trained to do so. As stated at \[64(a)(i)\] in _Mao_, there can be a causal or contributory link to the risk created by an offender’s act which leads to the actual harm caused.

85     Having said that, I would not go so far to say that but for the accused’s act of allowing Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift that day, the accident might have been prevented altogether as suggested by the Prosecution. Invariably, an accident occurs due to either an act of commission or omission by someone.

86     The accused’s act in this case had contributed to the death of the Deceased and this act is confined to having created an increased in risk for an accident occurring when he allowed Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift as compared to someone who is trained to or experienced in operating a forklift. An accident may still occur in the operation of a forklift but this risk is expected, and quite rightfully so, to be reduced when someone who is trained and perhaps even experienced is tasked to do so.

87     Another act which had contributed to the death of the Deceased was the act of creating an increased risk for the accident occurring when he allowed Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift with faulty brakes. This factor is quite apart from whether the accident was eventually attributable to the faulty brakes.

88     As such, even though the accused did not directly cause but contributed to the death of the Deceased, I disagreed with the Defence that harm in this case should be reduced to the higher end of moderate because the accused did not cause the actual harm.

89     I now come to the factors to consider for determining potential harm as stated at \[64(a)(i)\] in _Mao_.

90     The number of people likely to be exposed to the risk of harm that day was at least four. They were working at the Worksite at the material time. Based on the SOF, six employees were being assigned from Chye Joo to perform spray-painting works at the Worksite that day.

91     In respect of the seriousness of the harm risked, whilst this might not be as high as a situation involving work at heights, it could still be substantial. The operation of a forklift is a moving machinery and can be akin to driving a heavy vehicle like a lorry because of its size and weight. If not operated properly or driven in a safe manner, this can result in a serious accident where death or serious injury may occur.

92     Moreover, the Worksite was not a very large area and in fact rather confined. The driveway for a forklift to be driven and maneuvered was rather limited and not very wide. If a driver loses control of a forklift when transporting items, the risk of harm caused may be high. This can be so even if the distance travelled by the forklifts may not be long.

93     As for the likelihood of harm arising, this is increased when a forklift is used to load and transport materials, especially heavy or bulky items like a blasting pot. The likelihood of harm arising can also be high when a forklift that is used is not maintained in good working condition, for example having faulty brakes. In the present case, both the K-Forklift and M-Forklift at the Worksite had faulty brakes and were not maintained by the occupier in good working condition.

94     Following from there, when the accused authorised Shanmguam to operate the K-Forklift which had faulty brakes in his capacity as a supervisor even though Shanmugam was untrained to do so, the accused had contributed to the actual harm caused to the Deceased by creating a situation where there was an increase in the potential harm that might be caused in the circumstances. There was an increase in the seriousness of the harm risked as well as the likelihood of harm arising.

95     Another point to note is that, even though there was evidence that Shanmugam had been allowed to operate a forklift previously on other occasions without any incident, the fact remained that he was still untrained and not certified to do so and could not, based on the evidence, be treated as an experienced forklift operator.

96     Therefore, overall, I was of the view that the degree of harm, both actual and potential, in the present circumstances was still high.

#### Culpability

97     As for the culpability of the accused in relation to the reckless act, I was of the view that this was moderate and should be at the lower end of moderate.

98     In coming to my decision on Shanmugam’s sentence, I was of the view that his culpability was at the upper end of moderate. The Prosecution did not appeal against my decision on sentence for Shanmugam.

99     All things considered, I was of the view that the accused’s culpability as Shanmugam’s supervisor ought to be lower than and not equal to Shanmugam as submitted by the Prosecution in the present case. I now give my reasons.

100    I first deal with the number of unsafe and reckless acts committed by the accused. There were two as stated in the charge against the accused and these were allowing Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift:

> (i)     even though Shanmugam was an untrained forklift operator; and

> (ii)     when the brakes of the K-Forklift were faulty.

101    In comparison, Shanmugam committed three unsafe and reckless acts. These were operating the K-Forklift:

> (i)     without attaining the relevant training to do so;

> (ii)     with the knowledge that the K-Forklift’s brakes were faulty; and

> (iii)     in such a manner which resulted in the death of the Deceased.

102    On this point alone, the culpability of Shanmugam would be higher than that of the accused given that Shanmugam had committed an additional unsafe and reckless act from his manner of operating the K-Forklift which resulted in the Deceased’s death.

103    As for the nature of the unsafe act committed by the accused, the Prosecution accepted that this was a reckless act as compared to a wilful act. The accused’s act of allowing Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift which had faulty brakes when the latter was untrained to do so was a rash and perhaps foolhardy act, but it was not a deliberate and intentional act.

104    The Prosecution appeared to suggest that the accused and Shanmugam should receive a similar sentence because the accused, being the supervisor, had greater responsibilities and the authority not to permit the untrained Shanmugam from operating the K-Forklift.

105    I accepted that as Shanmugam’s supervisor, by allowing the untrained Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift at the material time, he is culpable and should be punished and not be let off scot-free even though he did not cause the accident. I also agreed that workplace safety is of paramount importance. Everyone has a part to play in ensuring safety at a workplace. Having said that, the fact that the accused had contributed indirectly to causing the death of the Deceased, this reckless act ought to be confined to his action of permitting Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift, whether with faulty brakes or not, when the latter was not trained to do so. It is distinct from the accident caused by Shanmugam’s act of operating the K-Forklift.

106    This is dissimilar to an abetment situation where an offender instigates, engages in conspiracy or intentionally aids someone to commit an offence by doing the offending act. The accused might have in a way abetted Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift without being trained but that did not extend to him abetting, facilitating or assisting Shanmugam to cause the accident. Shanmugam had a duty to operate the K-Forklift responsibly when he was permitted to do so.

107    In a nutshell, the accident happened on the material day as Shanmugam was driving the K-Forklift towards another blasting pot placed on the driveway and along the guardrail to transport it. This was a different blasting pot which the accused was transporting to the storage area using the M-Forklift.

108    The position of the forks was low. Shanmugam had to raise the forks of the K-Forklift in order to reach and lift the blasting pot. Unfortunately, he forgot that the K-Forklift was placed in the forward gear instead of neutral gear. He accidentally pressed on the acceleration pedal of the K-Forklift when he wanted to raise the forks. As a result, Shanmugam lost control of the K-Forklift and it suddenly accelerated forward, crashed through the guardrail, fell onto a slipway together with the blasting pot. The K-Forklift and blasting pot struck the Deceased who was walking along the slipway at the material time. Shanmugam also failed to take evasive action by pressing on the brake pedal of the K-Forklift when it surged forward.

109    In the earlier version of the SOF dated 12 May 2022 which was uploaded by the Prosecution, the phrase “as he knew the brakes were faulty.” was not included at paragraph 14 after the phrase “The accused did not press on the brake pedal as the K-Forklift surged forward”. This was only included in the version uploaded on 2 June 2022 but still dated 12 May 2022.

110    During mitigation, Defence Counsel confirmed and clarified that it was Shanmugam’s position that he was not speeding when driving the K-Forklift. There was also no evidence that Shanmugam was speeding. He forgot or thought that the K-Forklift was in neutral gear when he accidentally pressed on the acceleration pedal to lift the forks of the K-Forklift. Furthermore, the fact that Shanmugam knew that the brakes were faulty did not mean that this was the reason he did not press the brakes. That would have been an intentional and deliberate act. On the contrary, when the K-Forklift surged forward, it was more of his reaction at that time that he failed to apply the brakes in time or at all.

111    The fact remains is that the accident happened because of Shanmugam’s mistake of pressing on the acceleration pedal to raise the forks. Despite this mistake, he failed to react in time or take any evasive action by pressing on the brake pedal when the K-Forklift surged forward and this was not intentional. As such, the cause of the accident was not due to the faulty brakes. This fact was accepted by the Prosecution.

112    Put it in another way, the accident did not happen but for the accused’s action. The accident could still have happened in a similar manner even if a trained person had operated the K-Forklift. By allowing the untrained Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift, the accused had contributed to the death of the Deceased by increasing the risk of this harm occurring.

113    Next, the fact that the accused had operated the M-Forklift with the faulty brakes might have increased the likelihood of harm arising at the Worksite, but this did not cause or contribute to the death of the Deceased. It was undisputed by the Prosecution that from investigations, the forklifts at the Worksite were not in good working condition. It was also not disputed that the accused and Shanmugam were transporting the blasting pots as part of their works at the Worksite. The Prosecution accepted that the only way for the workers to perform this task was to use the forklifts. There was no deviation from established procedures to perform this particular task as such.

114    It would be pertinent to note that, on the material day, the accused did not instruct Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift in a reckless manner per se. Save for the fact that Shanmugam was untrained to operate a forklift and he had permitted this, the accused did not instruct Shanmugam to deviate from the usual safety procedure when operating the K-Forklift. There was no evidence that he had instructed Shanmugam to apply the acceleration pedal to raise the forks of the K-Forklift or follow any wrong procedure when operating it. There was also no evidence before me that he had instructed the accused not to press on the brake pedal in the event of an emergency or that he had instructed Shanmugam to operate the K-Forklift dangerously to perform the task.

115    Prosecution submitted that as the supervisor, the accused could have refused to comply with instructions to perform the works using the forklifts with faulty brakes, especially given that this was a deviation from established procedures where only forklifts in good working condition should be used.

116    In my view, perhaps this would be too onerous a duty to be placed on the accused given the circumstances, especially since there was no suggestion that he has failed to comply with or breached any RA pertaining to safe operation of forklifts. The fact that he was involved in the review of a RA for using forklifts in work activities such as grit blasting and spray painting (the RA was not an evidence before me) would only go towards showing that the accused knew or ought to know that he should not allow someone to operate the K-Forklift if that person is untrained, whether the brakes were faulty or otherwise or whether this was an isolated occasion or not.

117    Furthermore, one of the forklift operators of the occupier was seen using at least the M-Forklift prior to the accident. Permission was also given to the accused to use the forklifts at the Worksite on more than one occasion. Regrettably, even though this was not the first time that the accused and even Shanmugam had operated the forklifts with the faulty brakes at the Worksite, the workers could only rely on these forklifts to transport the blasting pots within the Worksite on that material day.

118    Whilst I agreed that the issue was systemic at the Worksite and unsatisfactory, unfortunately, it was not an issue that the accused could resolve despite his best endeavours in the circumstances. The Prosecution accepted that the workers had informed the maintenance team of the occupier the problems with the condition of the forklifts at the Worksite including the faulty brakes. The pressure of the brake pedals of the forklifts was found to be low and one needs to step on the pedal until it was almost touching the floor.

119    As regards the use and operation of the K-Forklift with faulty brakes, I reiterated that ultimately the accident which resulted in the death of the Deceased was not due to the faulty brakes based on the evidence before me. Even if I am wrong, the fact remains that the accused was not in charge of maintaining the forklifts at the Worksite which belonged to the occupier.

120    The main problem with the forklifts at the Worksite was that there was a systemic failure on the part of the occupier to maintain them properly such that they were not in good working condition. Presumably, this issue was not dealt with effectively or at all and any motivation to save cost in the circumstances would really be attributable to the occupier. This once again shows that at the end of the day, everyone plays an important part in ensuring workplace safety.

121    In the circumstances, I accorded less weight on the faulty brakes issue in terms of culpability against the accused.

122    In addition, the circumstances in which the accident had occurred in the present case can be contrasted with a situation where the entire unsafe system of works was permitted by the supervisor and this unsafe system of works had directly caused the death of or harm to a worker e.g. in _Mao_ where the offender was a supervisor who was in charge of the lifting operations of formworks and he failed to ensure that the deceased was provided with safety equipment like a lifeline or had anchored himself to a safety harness to the guardrail for work at heights before instructing the deceased to proceed. There was a direct causal link to the supervisor for the actual harm caused to the deceased. In view of the offender’s high degree of harm and culpability in _Mao_, he was sentenced to 12 months’ imprisonment for his negligent act.

123    This can be contrasted with a situation where the offender was a supervisor and he had permitted his co-worker to operate a lorry to deliver goods from one location to another when he knew that the co-worker did not have the relevant driving licence in Singapore to do so. The co-worker drove the lorry and caused an accident resulting in the death of someone. The offender would be liable for permitting the co-worker to drive the lorry without a valid driving licence as well as insurance and be punished accordingly. He would, however, not be liable for the accident caused by the co-worker. As rightly pointed out by both the Prosecution and Defence, it would be too remote to directly attribute the death of someone as a result of the accident caused by the co-worker to the offender.

124    For the above reasons, I was of the view that for the accused’s contributory link towards the Deceased’s death, the culpability of the accused should be less than Shanmugam and at the lower end of moderate culpability.

125    Applying the proposed sentencing framework, the indicative sentencing range for the accused would be more than nine months and up to 15 months’ imprisonment for high harm-moderate culpability.

126    I then analysed the cases submitted by the Prosecution where the offender had been charged and convicted under s 15(3) of WHSA for committing a reckless act.

127    In the cases of _Wong_ and _Yee_ which involved the collapse of a section of the viaduct spanning from the Tampines Expressway to Pan Island Expressway, both the offenders had claimed trial and were convicted. One death occurred and ten other employees were injured. The court held that harm was high in both cases. _Yee_’s culpability was found to be higher than _Wong_ and fell squarely within the moderate category as he had not only failed to call for a stoppage of works when he was informed of fresh cracks which appeared on the day prior to the collapse, he had prior knowledge of cracks appearing on multiple corbels of the viaduct as early as weeks before the collapse. Yee ‘s indicative sentence was 13 months’ imprisonment but was eventually sentenced to ten months’ imprisonment.

128    As for _Wong_, his culpability fell within the lower end of the moderate range as he had failed to execute a stop work order prior to the collapse of the viaduct when he knew that the presence of the corbel cracks on that fateful day represented an obvious sign of danger. _Wong_’s indicative sentence was 11 months’ imprisonment but was eventually sentenced to eight months’ imprisonment.

129    As for the case of _Mamun_, harm caused was moderate as the victim sustained serious injuries or grievous hurt. However, the culpability of the offender in Mamun was high. He was not only a safety supervisor at the worksite who was aware of any safety protocols, but he had also operated the forklift on his own accord when he was untrained to do so. In fact, he had created a deception by relying on a forged certificate as proof that he was approved with the relevant competency to operate the forklift. On the day of the accident, the offender had operated the forklift dangerously when he maneuvered the forklift with its mast raised. He also drove the forklift at a high speed.

130    The offender collided into the victim who was standing next to a lorry to unload materials from it because the offender could not see the victim with the mast of the forklift raised. Thus, when he eventually saw the victim, he could not stop in time as he was speeding. Overall, I sentenced the offender to 45 weeks’ imprisonment for causing death by performing a reckless act (42 weeks’ imprisonment) and operating the forklift with a forged certificate (3 weeks’ imprisonment.

131    Hence, based on the evidence in totality, whilst I agreed that the harm caused in the present case with one dead and one injured worker was certainly greater than in _Mamun_, I disagreed with the Prosecution that the culpability of Shanmugam was greater than that in _Mamun_. If at all, in my view, the harm and culpability factors for both cases appeared to somewhat balance up each other. As such, I placed the indicative starting sentence for Shanmugam at 14 months’ imprisonment and eventually sentenced him to 11 months’ imprisonment having taken into account his mitigating factors.

132    All in all, on the facts, I was further of the view that the accused’s culpability in the present case should not be higher than in _Wong, Yee, Mamun_ and even _Mao_. Here, I placed the indicative starting sentence for the accused at ten months’ imprisonment.

133    I agreed with both parties to apply a downward adjustment of three months to take into account mitigating factors, including the fact that the accused has pleaded guilty at the first available opportunity, cooperated fully with investigations, is remorseful and untraced.

134    All things considered, I was of the view that a sentence of seven months’ imprisonment to be imposed on the accused is appropriate. Additionally, I backdated the accused sentence to the date of his remand on 22 March 2022.

## Conclusion

135    To summarise, the accused was accordingly sentenced as follows:
